<br>
I was watching a neat little show while playing trivia at the bar the other day and it listed the various pork barrel politics on both sides of the aisle that were just absurd.  I found most of the ones they listed and a few more on the CAGW website.  It's an interesting read if you ever have the time to peruse it.<br>
<br>
<br>
The funniest to me were:<br>
 - The $500,000 issue to each Rep/Senator for sending postcards to constituents.  <br>
 - The $3000-6000 raises for themselves, they've done such a good job why not vote another cost of living increase.<br>
 - 1.4 Million Dollars for a Kennel Complex (That's for dogs if you were unaware) at Elmendorf Air Force Base.<br>
 - $202,500 for a National Peanut Festival into economic development appropriations.<br>
 - Appropriators from the Departments of Commerce, Justice and State diverted millions away from the war on terror to fund pet projects, such as the First Tee Program, which dedicates $500,000 toward the construction of new golf courses for &quot;young people . who have not previously had exposure to the game..&quot;<br>
 - Hidden away in the recesses of the 2002 Defense Appropriations Bill, was a $3 million deal to lease 100 fuel tankers from Boeing. The General Accounting Office estimates that the six-year lease will cost taxpayers up to $30 billion. GAO reported that it would cost approximately $23 billion less to upgrade the current fleet.<br>
 - Tucked into the 2003 Labor/HHS/Education Appropriations Bill was an $800,000 gift to the Grammy Foundation for music and arts education.<br>
 - Appropriators handed out $500,000 to the International Coffee Organization, whose professed goal is to stimulate the coffee economy. <br>
<br>
In addition, many on both sides of the aisle are fighting against resolution, S. Res. 173, would allow any senator to raise a point of order against appropriations earmarks.  Such items are not specifically authorized by law, and also skirt the competitive process.  Introduced by the Senate’s number one pork-barrel critic, Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz), and co-sponsored by Sens. Jon Kyl (R-Ariz.), Jeff Sessions (R-Ala.) and Russ Feingold (D-Wis.), the resolution would require 60 votes to keep an earmark in a bill.  S. Res. 173 would give all senators the opportunity to object to provisions inserted by members of the Appropriations Committee into the spending bills and subject them to a separate vote.<br>
<br>
Basically this bill would allow senators to zap shit like the Peanut Festival and Dog Kennel, but the number one critics of the bill are yes.. you guessed it.. the people who are chewing on the pork.<br>
<br>
Unfortunately the only way to get rid of these momo's who keep passing this shit is to vote them out of office.. and do you think the guy who just got a job building the new Elmendorf AFB Dog Kennel is going to vote out of office the guy who just got him a job? <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=204898">Ayiar Frullaniaceae</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
