<br>
What's increased steadily over time is the National Debt.  It dropped briefly during Clinton's second term, but it's pretty much been steadily increasing as well ever since a massive increase post-WW2.<br>
<br>
Nobody really turned the economy around since it hasn't been going down for a while now (During vietnam were the last substantial recessions), Clinton just had a bit more effect in cutting the pork, and Reagan was considered a direhard Military guy who increased spending substantially.  Not 100% sure this is all accurate, but it's pretty much what I remember reading about when growing up.  Carter was a bit before my time. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=204898">Ayiar Frullaniaceae</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.vazaelle.dk">Caer Cadarn</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mrbanderas>Mr Banderas</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Senior Member</span><br>  Posts: 729<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(7/15/03 1:21 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wow that's a big ass deficit</span><hr size=1> Yeah, I probably should have been more clear.  I stated the terms in the correct manner but I didn't make it more obvious to a person that doesn't know what I meant by it.<br>
<br>
Ayiar pretty much nailed it.  Reagan was a huge spender and didn't do a very good job with the budget.  This is independent of the economy.  For the most part, the economy was pretty stable while he was in office, although it never really moved forward either.  His problem was his overspending started the deficit moving in exponential increases.<br>
<br>
When Bush Sr. took office he controlled spending better although he also did put a lot into the military.  The deficit still rose but it was a bit more controlled at this point, whereas with Reagan it was pretty hard to predict how it would move.  Bush Sr. did a better job with economics than Reagan although some could say he was aided by the war, which is another debate altogether.  <br>
<br>
Clinton came in and did a good job with the budget, for some reason he was very skillful at maniuplating it and did a better job with it than the last few Presidents before him.  As far as the economy, he did a decent job with it although a lot of the credit has to go to the steadily building-up from Bush Sr.'s term as well as the international market changes due to new technological powers.  The strengthening of the currency of nations outside of us was a nice boost in our imports and exports and surely contributed to where we are today.  Clinton deserves some credit, yes, but not all of it.  <br>
<br>
Since then the economy has hit a large recession, whether it be Clinton's fault, Bush's fault, or neither's fault, it doesn't really matter at this point.  What does matter is that in times of recession, government spending should, theoretically, go up, and currently it seems like it's only being done at levels with little to no return.  This isn't a knock on Bush, as we have no idea yet how things are going to change in the next few months.  Hindsight is 20/20 and there's never any way of knowing exaclty how an economy is going to react to changes.  If it were that easy, we wouldn't have people debating it.  Historically, we're supposed to go through ups and downs, the only reason this recession hit us as hard as it did is because we had such an extended time of prosperity beforehand.  The longer the time between recessions, the harder the fall when they come.<br>
<br>
The resources for economists nowadays are so much better than they were in the past, so I have trust that the Reserve and the government will make the right choices in getting this country back on track.  I think the role of the President, in general, in controlling the economy is slowly starting to diminish and the role of foreign policy is beginning to take center stage.  The future of the world appears to be taking a turn towards amicable dependency, so its imperative that our next few Presidents take tenacious grasps onto relations with the other powers of the world to work together.  There will never be world peace but I'd venture to guess that whoever coined the term would be satisfactory with applying it to the current situation of the international community, and hopefully it should improve.<br>
<br>
In brief summary:  I don't think the deficit/economy are so much a reflection of the President's anymore as they are of the international market, the Reserve, and the current peace/wartime affairs. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=aurianne>Aurianne</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_fire.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Mana Whore</span><br>  Posts: 1653<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(7/15/03 1:21 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=133.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wow that's a big ass deficit</span><hr size=1> Huh. Your annual defeceit is larger than our national debt. (Our debt is $545 billion CAD as of 2002.)<br>
