<br>
I think Ayiar hit the nail on the head here.  We all look at the big programs when we want to cut spending, but we could save a hell of a lot by cutting all the little useless stuff like peanut festivals and bear dna sampling.  The problem is that the pork barrel spending is good for the individual state economies, even though all the states would be better off if we did away with all of it.<br>
<br>
As far as Reagan, despite the fact that he ran deficits, I think he is basically responsible for the huge economic growth we've seen over the last 22 years.  Taxes were so high back then that they removed incentive to work, and under Reagan, tax revenues actually went up after the tax cuts were enacted because of the massive effects on the economy that reduced taxation produced.  In Reagan's term, we really were at a point on the laffer curve where cutting tax rates (which were over 90 percent at the top) increased revenue.<br>
<br>
The deficits did spur the economy and gave us record growth, the problem is that the deficits were meant to be a temporary situation, not a new way of life, and unfortunately, they have become a way of life.<br>
<br>
Clinton's success in balancing the budget came from the soaring stock markets.  As people took profits on their stock sales, they paid taxes, and federal revenues went up.  He didn't actually do much to control spending.  If we go into a period of great economic prosperity soon, the deficits will likely shrink substantially.  However, I'm skeptical that that can erase $450 billion of deficit.<br>
